---
import SiteLayout from "../components/SiteLayout.astro";
---

<SiteLayout
  title="Astropress Getting Started"
  description="Start Astropress with the local SQLite-backed flow, understand what is supported today, and use the CLI without guessing at the product boundary."
  heading="Start with the local path that Astropress validates most heavily."
  currentPath="/docs"
>
  <section class="panel-grid">
    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Quick start</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><code>astropress new my-site</code></li>
        <li><code>cd my-site</code></li>
        <li><code>bun install</code></li>
        <li><code>astropress doctor</code></li>
        <li><code>astropress dev</code></li>
      </ol>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Default release posture</h2>
      <p>
        Treat the local SQLite-backed admin and the static public example as the reference implementation. Move to
        hosted adapters when you need them, but do not assume every hosted path has the same maturity today.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="panel-grid">
    <article class="panel">
      <h2>Two setup choices</h2>
      <p>
        Astropress now separates <strong>App Host</strong> from <strong>Content Services</strong>. App Host means
        where the Astro app runs. Content Services means where Astropress stores content, media, auth, sessions, and
        the service API that powers admin actions.
      </p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
      <h2>CLI examples</h2>
      <ol>
        <li><code>astropress new my-site --app-host vercel --content-services supabase</code></li>
        <li><code>astropress new brochure --app-host github-pages --content-services none</code></li>
        <li><code>astropress new team-site --app-host cloudflare-pages --content-services cloudflare</code></li>
      </ol>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="panel">
    <h2>What editors get</h2>
    <p>
      Package-owned admin routes cover pages, posts, media, redirects, comments, users, translations, settings, and
      revisions. The intended workflow is editor-first, not Git-first.
    </p>
    <p>
      Git sync remains useful for export, backup, review, and static deploy workflows, but the content database is the
      canonical source of truth.
    </p>
  </section>

  <section class="panel">
    <h2>Read next</h2>
    <p>
      Use <a href="/providers">Hosting</a> for app-host and content-services fit, <a href="/wordpress">WordPress</a> for
      import scope, and <a href="/operations">Operations</a> for backup, restore, and health checks.
    </p>
  </section>
</SiteLayout>
